<HEADLINE>
<P>
DROPPING OUT; RATE DECLINES AT VALLEY HIGH SCHOOLS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A majority of the 16 regular high schools in the San Fernando Valley recorded 
a decline in dropout rates last year, according to Los Angeles Unified School 
District figures released last week. Districtwide, the number of dropouts -- 
decreased from 15.28% to 13.51%. 
</P>
<P>
 The dropout rates -- which the district began recording in 1985 -- show the 
actual number of students who missed more than 45 days of school without 
officially transferring to another school or alternative education program. 
</P>
<P>
 The state Department of Education uses a different method to calculate dropout 
rates, projecting figures over a three-year period to show how many 10th grade 
students actually finish high school. The 1991-1992 state figure for the 
district was about 37%. Los Angeles Unified School District 
</P>
<P>
 Total enrollment: 640,000. Grades K to 12. Dropout rates for LAUSD schools 
appear below. Valley high schools appear with an asterisk (*): 
