<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: HUNTINGTON BEACH; CITY ADMINISTRATOR TO GET 11% PAY RAISE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MARY LOU PICKEL 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 City Administrator Michael T. Uberuaga will receive an 11% salary increase 
starting in February, the City Council decided Monday. 
</P>
<P>
 The raise was approved by a 4-3 vote and will put Uberuaga's salary at 
$142,457. 
</P>
<P>
 Councilman Ralph Bauer said Uberuaga has "done a fine job and I think he's 
saved us some money." 
</P>
<P>
 But Councilman David Sullivan said he could not vote for the raise.  
</P>
<P>
 "There are a lot of people who have done good jobs during this recession and 
they haven't gotten increases," he said. Mayor Linda Moulton-Patterson and 
Councilman Jim Silva also voted against the raise.  
</P>
<P>
 Uberuaga began as city administrator four years ago and has not received a pay 
raise since 1991. The 11% raise would equal the increases that other city 
department heads have received since 1991, Uberuaga said. MARY LOU PICKEL 
</P>
</TEXT>
